hook.real_world_problem:
Every Java app you build will eventually read or write files. A Flipkart order importer reads CSV files. A Zerodha report generator writes Excel-ready data. A Razorpay config loader reads JSON from disk. A log analyser processes thousands of log lines.

The old Java way:
```java
// java.io.File — clunky, error-prone:
File file = new File("data/orders.csv");
BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
String line;
while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) { process(line); }
reader.close();  // must close manually!
// Exceptions everywhere, no stream support, terrible API
```

**The modern way — Java NIO.2 (java.nio.file):**
```java
// Path + Files — clean, safe, stream-friendly:
Path path = Path.of("data/orders.csv");

// Read all lines:
List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(path);

// Or as a stream (lazy, memory-efficient for huge files):
try (Stream<String> stream = Files.lines(path)) {
    stream.filter(line -> !line.startsWith("#"))
          .forEach(this::processOrder);
}

// Write:
Files.writeString(path, content);
Files.write(path, lines);
```

Clean. Type-safe. Stream-integrated. Auto-closeable. This is the modern Java way to work with files.

concept_explanation.path_interface:
**`Path` — represents a file or directory location:**

```java
import java.nio.file.*;

// Create a Path:
Path p1 = Path.of("data/orders.csv");           // relative path
Path p2 = Path.of("/home/aisha/data/orders.csv"); // absolute path
Path p3 = Path.of("data", "orders", "april.csv"); // varargs join

// Path navigation:
Path parent = p1.getParent();   // data
Path filename = p1.getFileName(); // orders.csv
String ext = p1.toString().substring(p1.toString().lastIndexOf('.'));

// Resolve (join paths):
Path dir  = Path.of("data");
Path file = dir.resolve("orders.csv");  // data/orders.csv
Path up   = dir.resolve("../reports"); // data/../reports

// Normalize (remove . and ..):
Path clean = up.normalize();  // reports

// Absolute path:
Path abs = p1.toAbsolutePath();  // /current/working/dir/data/orders.csv

// Path info:
System.out.println(p3.getNameCount());  // 3 (data, orders, april.csv)
System.out.println(p3.getName(0));      // data
System.out.println(p3.getName(2));      // april.csv
```

**Path vs String**: Path knows about the OS (uses `/` on Unix, `\` on Windows). `Path.of()` handles separator differences automatically.

concept_explanation.files_read:
**Reading files with `Files`:**

```java
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;

Path path = Path.of("data/orders.csv");

// Read all lines into List<String> (good for small-medium files):
List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(path);  // default: UTF-8
List<String> lines2 = Files.readAllLines(path, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);

// Read entire file as String (Java 11+):
String content = Files.readString(path);

// Read as byte array (binary files, images, etc.):
byte[] bytes = Files.readAllBytes(path);

// Stream lines — lazy, memory-efficient for large files:
try (Stream<String> stream = Files.lines(path)) {
    long count = stream
        .filter(line -> !line.isBlank())
        .count();
}
// IMPORTANT: Always use try-with-resources for Files.lines() — it opens a file handle!
```

concept_explanation.files_write:
**Writing files with `Files`:**

```java
Path path = Path.of("output/report.txt");

// Write String to file (creates or replaces):
Files.writeString(path, "Hello, Hyderabad!");

// Write String with options:
Files.writeString(path, "New line\n",
    StandardOpenOption.APPEND,   // append instead of overwrite
    StandardOpenOption.CREATE);  // create if doesn't exist

// Write list of lines:
List<String> lines = Arrays.asList("Line 1", "Line 2", "Line 3");
Files.write(path, lines);  // each element on a new line

// Write bytes (for binary data):
byte[] data = imageData;
Files.write(path, data);

// StandardOpenOption values:
// CREATE         — create file if not exists
// CREATE_NEW     — fail if file already exists
// APPEND         — append to existing content
// TRUNCATE_EXISTING — truncate to zero before writing (default for write)
// WRITE          — open for writing
```

concept_explanation.files_copy_move:
**Copying and moving files:**

```java
Path src  = Path.of("data/orders.csv");
Path dest = Path.of("backup/orders-2024.csv");

// Copy:
Files.copy(src, dest);  // fails if dest exists
Files.copy(src, dest, StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);  // overwrite OK
Files.copy(src, dest, StandardCopyOption.COPY_ATTRIBUTES);   // copy metadata too

// Move (rename):
Files.move(src, dest);
Files.move(src, dest, StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);
Files.move(src, dest, StandardCopyOption.ATOMIC_MOVE);  // atomic on same filesystem

// Copy with progress (InputStream-based):
try (InputStream in = Files.newInputStream(src)) {
    Files.copy(in, dest);  // from input stream to file
}
```

concept_explanation.files_walk:
**Walking directory trees:**

```java
Path dir = Path.of("data");

// List immediate children:
try (Stream<Path> entries = Files.list(dir)) {
    entries.forEach(System.out::println);
}

// Walk all files recursively (depth-first):
try (Stream<Path> walk = Files.walk(dir)) {
    walk.filter(Files::isRegularFile)   // only files, skip dirs
        .filter(p -> p.toString().endsWith(".csv"))
        .forEach(p -> System.out.println("Found CSV: " + p));
}

// Walk with depth limit:
try (Stream<Path> walk = Files.walk(dir, 2)) {
    // Only 2 levels deep
}

// Find files matching a predicate:
try (Stream<Path> found = Files.find(dir, Integer.MAX_VALUE,
        (path, attrs) -> attrs.isRegularFile() && path.toString().endsWith(".json"))) {
    found.forEach(System.out::println);
}

// IMPORTANT: ALL of Files.list(), Files.walk(), Files.find() return streams
// that hold open file handles — always use try-with-resources!
```

concept_explanation.old_file_vs_path:
**Old `java.io.File` vs new `java.nio.file.Path`:**

```java
// OLD — java.io.File (avoid in new code):
File file = new File("data/orders.csv");
file.exists();
file.length();
BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
// Problems: no stream support, clunky API, error handling verbose

// NEW — java.nio.file (use this):
Path path = Path.of("data/orders.csv");
Files.exists(path);
Files.size(path);
List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(path);
Stream<String> lines = Files.lines(path);

// Converting between old and new:
Path fromFile = file.toPath();     // File → Path
File fromPath = path.toFile();     // Path → File (for old APIs)
```

You'll still see `java.io.File` in older code — it's important to recognize it, but always use `Path` + `Files` in new code.

